<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-600-813  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 600 813.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Engineering  Oct 1990 v22 n10 p44(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The critical imperative in flexible manufacturing is information;flexible manufacturing is more than automated equipment on thefactory floor - it is business strategy powered by a totalenterprise, integrated information architecture. (Issue Focus:Flexible Manufacturing Systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rhodes, Dusty.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Research done at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)indicates that manufacturing management must master informationtechnology to stay competitive in the 1990s.andP;  Competitivepressures are certain to increase, and the consequence is thatcompanies must learn to do everything well, from design, tomanufacturing, to customer service.andP;  There will be almost nomargin for error.andP;  Top management must view flexible manufacturingsystems (FMSs) as only a tactical part of a much broader strategicpicture.andP;  For FMS to be strategic, a view of it must not berestricted to a perception of equipment on the factory floor.andP;  FMSmust be understood as integrated within an enterprisewidecomputing environment, linked into the corporate planning systemsthat drive the organization.andP;  Information must therefore beavailable, to be used within a time frame that makes a difference.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Flexible manufacturing systemsIndustrial engineeringFactory managementManufacturingMISInformation Resources ManagementMassachusetts Institute of Technology.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechartgraph.andO;Caption:   Phases of technology. (table)Competitive information strategy. (chart)Manufacturing industry technology trends. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>